{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"29e0aef4-efae-4205-bbfd-fbabf2b95b1e","content":"The repository is empty, so this isn't a repo-specific question. Here's the general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS (NativeAOT, no `createdump`)\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump`. On macOS, use the **OS-native crash reporting** instead:\n\n1. **Check for Apple crash logs** — macOS automatically writes crash reports to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for a `.ips` or `.crash` file matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before reproducing:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n   mkdir -p /tmp/cores\n   ```\n   Then rerun the app. A core file will appear in `/tmp/cores/`.\n\n3. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Use `bt` (backtrace), `thread list`, `register read`, etc.\n\n4. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, you may need to temporarily disable System Integrity Protection or sign your binary with the `com.apple.security.get-task-allow` entitlement:\n   ```bash\n   codesign -s - --entitlements entitlements.plist /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   where `entitlements.plist` includes `com.apple.security.get-task-allow = true`.\n\n5. **Alternative — use `dotnet-dump collect`** if targeting a CoreCLR host (not applicable to pure NativeAOT, but worth noting for mixed scenarios).\n\n**Key point**: On macOS + NativeAOT, you rely on the OS crash reporter and `lldb` rather than .NET-specific tooling.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"806c1751-e67a-4e8d-8f71-b7abf34eca6e","outputTokens":455,"requestId":"980F:3387D:5423135:5CB62F6:69F406D1"},"id":"f3418130-5601-4952-9dbf-9388a2e408d0","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:50:21.289Z","parentId":"ab92f512-b346-4f32-9c34-cd95cfdace85"}
